#Detailed Analysis
##Navigation
To build the navigation bar, I took the image that AJ designed on our mock-up page and tried to emulate it as closely as possible. I decided to break it out into three different components which I would then import into one single component that would act as the overall container and border holding it all together. For the first two components(the profile picture and left-hand navigation buttons), I utilized Material-UI which has some amazing looking pre-built components, but has a slightly steeper learning curve and more complications than the average library. Material-UI uses it's own form of styled-components which takes a little bit getting used to, and while thorough, the docs can be a little bit intimidating with how much there is to pick up on. The first issue I encountered was in choosing which source code option to test and incorporate into my code. Naturally I reached for the source code labeled for React, but I soon found out that this was incompatible with my codebase/dependencies as React hooks (which the example was implementing) is only supported by a very specific alpha version of React. The Github source code I tried next appeared to work fine, so I continued building out the navigation. Upon integrating the next component from Material-UI, I made the same mistake again and was met with an error, jogging my memory. Upon switching to the Github source code however, I was also met with an error. My third option was to try the source code that appeared to be labeled vanilla Javascript which I dreaded would become a million lines of code, but upon a closer look it was just regular React which integrated with my code perfectly. The next problem I encountered was that the Material-UI buttons I had imported were drawing in css characteristics from my seperate Signup/Login buttons I had built and to make a long story short, I had to use a special override feature found in the documentation to fix the problem. Getting the buttons and profile picture to render exactly as I wanted proved to become a bit of a struggle as I researched forums and codesandbox demo's of example work-arounds and insight to how everything worked. Ultimately I settled upon a very close picture to what AJ had drawn up and gained a lot more knowledge of how Material-UI works, which I hope will pay dividends as we continue further with the project.

As a part of your journal entry, write ¼ to ½ a page reflecting on your experiences forming a team. What did you do to help the team solidify as a group? What did you do that you now realize caused friction in this process?

#Forming as a Team
I believe my team has formed together particularly well. All of us are open enough to speak up with our own ideas, but also willing to defer in favor of the the collective group sentiment if it is leaning in another direction. As a team, it helps to have people that are self-aware and willing to go with the flow in the interest of better collaboration. In the beginning stages when we were planning and I was just getting to know my teammates, I wasn't as in tune with their personalities, so while I initially wanted the team dynamic to look like previous teams I had worked on, I realized that this would only cause friction and that I should focus on creating a dynamic that would better align with the people I was working with. Upon realizing the general group personality, I have worked towards trying to make sure everyone's input is heard while also encouraging them to not become too laissez-faire in going along with the group so that we don't lose out on valuable input.
